The results presented in Table 2 show that replacing the atom C by a substitutional anionic atom N or O reduces the total electron energy of quantum dot while inserting a cation atom B in place of C results in an increase in the total electron energy of quantum dot. On the other hand, inserting an atom B and N in the place of the central C atom increase the difference between the total energy of the ideal dot and the dot with vacancy in the middle compared to that difference for C whereas insertion of O results in decreasing this energy difference. From Table II it is also seen that taking into account the lattice distortion for O (O
                        def
                     ) results in a further reduction of the total energy of the system.
